.SH "Detailed Description"
.PP 
Curved path defined by control points, supporting multiple spline types including cubic Bezier curves\&. 

Splines are mathematical curves defined by control points\&. PDG supports several spline types:

.PP
.IP "\(bu" 2
\fBspline_Hermite\fP - Hermite spline using position and tangent vector parameters
.IP "\(bu" 2
\fBspline_Cardinal\fP - Cardinal (Catmull-Rom) spline that passes through all control points
.IP "\(bu" 2
\fBspline_UniformB\fP - Uniform B-spline for smooth curves
.IP "\(bu" 2
\fBspline_CubicBezier\fP - Cubic Bezier curves with control handles
.IP "\(bu" 2
\fBspline_TCB\fP - Tension-Continuity-Bias spline for animation curves
.IP "\(bu" 2
\fBspline_NaturalCubic\fP - Natural cubic spline with continuous second derivatives
.PP
.SH "Hermite Spline Parameters"
.PP
When using \fBspline_Hermite\fP, the four parameters to \fBaddSegment()\fP are:
.IP "\(bu" 2
\fBp1\fP - Start position (\fBPoint\fP)
.IP "\(bu" 2
\fBp2\fP - End position (\fBPoint\fP)
.IP "\(bu" 2
\fBp3\fP - Tangent \fBvector\fP at start (\fBPoint\fP used as a direction vector, not a position)
.IP "\(bu" 2
\fBp4\fP - Tangent \fBvector\fP at end (\fBPoint\fP used as a direction vector, not a position)
.PP

.PP
\fBNote\fP
.RS 4
The tangent parameters (p3, p4) are \fBdirection vectors\fP, not positions\&. They control the direction and speed of the curve as it leaves the start point and approaches the end point\&.
.RE
.PP
\fBHermite Example:\fP
.RS 4

.PP
.nf
var spline = new pdg\&.Spline(pdg\&.spline_Hermite);
spline\&.addSegment(
    new pdg\&.Point(10, 10),   // p1: start position
    new pdg\&.Point(100, 50),  // p2: end position  
    new pdg\&.Point(30, 0),    // p3: tangent vector (direction/speed leaving start)
    new pdg\&.Point(30, 0)     // p4: tangent vector (direction/speed approaching end)
);

.fi
.PP
 
.RE
.PP

.SH "Member Function Documentation"
.PP 
.SS "addPoint (\fBPoint\fP point)"

.PP
adds a control point to the spline This low-level method adds a single control point to the spline\&. The meaning and usage of control points depends on the spline type:

.PP
\fBHermite Splines (spline_Hermite):\fP
.RS 4
Points are added in groups of 4: position1, position2, tangent_vector1, tangent_vector2\&. For Hermite splines, tangent points (3rd and 4th in each group) should be \fBdirection vectors\fP, not positions\&. Use \fBaddSegment()\fP instead for easier Hermite spline creation\&.
.RE
.PP
\fBCubic Bezier Splines (spline_CubicBezier):\fP
.RS 4
Points are added in groups of 4: start, control1, control2, end\&. Additional segments share the endpoint of the previous segment\&.
.RE
.PP
\fBCardinal/Catmull-Rom Splines (spline_Cardinal):\fP
.RS 4
Each point is a position that the curve passes through\&. The curve is calculated using a sliding window of 4 consecutive points\&.
.RE
.PP
\fBUniform B-Splines (spline_UniformB):\fP
.RS 4
Each point is a control point\&. The curve approximates the shape defined by these points but doesn't necessarily pass through them\&.
.RE
.PP
\fBNote\fP
.RS 4
For most use cases, \fBaddSegment()\fP provides a more intuitive interface, especially for Hermite and Bezier splines\&. Use \fBaddPoint()\fP when you need fine-grained control over individual points or when building multi-segment Cardinal or B-splines\&.
.RE
.PP
\fBParameters\fP
.RS 4
\fIpoint\fP the control point to add (interpretation depends on spline type)
.RE
.PP
\fBSee also\fP
.RS 4
\fBaddSegment()\fP, \fBgetPoint()\fP, \fBsetPoint()\fP, \fBgetPointCount()\fP 
.RE
.PP

.SS "addSegment (\fBPoint\fP p1, \fBPoint\fP p2, \fBPoint\fP p3, \fBPoint\fP p4)"

.PP
adds a spline segment with four control points The meaning of the four points depends on the spline type:

.PP
\fBHermite Splines (spline_Hermite):\fP
.RS 4

.IP "\(bu" 2
\fBp1\fP - Start position (\fBPoint\fP)
.IP "\(bu" 2
\fBp2\fP - End position (\fBPoint\fP)
.IP "\(bu" 2
\fBp3\fP - Tangent \fBvector\fP at start (NOT a position, but a direction vector)
.IP "\(bu" 2
\fBp4\fP - Tangent \fBvector\fP at end (NOT a position, but a direction vector)
.PP
.RE
.PP
\fBWarning\fP
.RS 4
For Hermite splines, p3 and p4 are \fBtangent vectors\fP (directions), not positions\&. They control the direction and speed of the curve at the start and end points\&. To create identical curves that are offset in position, use the same tangent vectors with different start/end positions\&.
.RE
.PP
\fBCubic Bezier Splines (spline_CubicBezier):\fP
.RS 4

.IP "\(bu" 2
\fBp1\fP - Start position
.IP "\(bu" 2
\fBp2\fP - First control point (handle)
.IP "\(bu" 2
\fBp3\fP - Second control point (handle)
.IP "\(bu" 2
\fBp4\fP - End position
.PP
.RE
.PP
\fBCardinal/Catmull-Rom Splines (spline_Cardinal):\fP
.RS 4

.IP "\(bu" 2
\fBp1\fP, \fBp2\fP, \fBp3\fP, \fBp4\fP - Four consecutive control points
.IP "\(bu" 2
The curve passes through p2 and p3, using p1 and p4 to calculate tangents
.PP
.RE
.PP
\fBOther Spline Types:\fP
.RS 4
The four points serve as control points according to each spline type's mathematical definition\&.
.RE
.PP
\fBExample - Hermite with tangent vectors:\fP
.RS 4

.PP
.nf
var spline = new pdg\&.Spline(pdg\&.spline_Hermite);
spline\&.addSegment(
    new pdg\&.Point(0, 0),     // p1: start position
    new pdg\&.Point(100, 50),  // p2: end position
    new pdg\&.Point(30, 20),   // p3: tangent vector (go right 30, up 20)
    new pdg\&.Point(30, \-10)   // p4: tangent vector (arrive going right 30, down 10)
);

.fi
.PP
.RE
.PP
\fBExample - Cubic Bezier:\fP
.RS 4

.PP
.nf
var bezier = new pdg\&.Spline(pdg\&.spline_CubicBezier);
bezier\&.addSegment(
    new pdg\&.Point(0, 0),     // start point
    new pdg\&.Point(25, 75),   // first control handle
    new pdg\&.Point(75, 25),   // second control handle
    new pdg\&.Point(100, 100)  // end point
);

.fi
.PP
.RE
.PP
\fBParameters\fP
.RS 4
\fIp1\fP first control point (meaning depends on spline type) 
.br
\fIp2\fP second control point (meaning depends on spline type) 
.br
\fIp3\fP third control point (meaning depends on spline type) 
.br
\fIp4\fP fourth control point (meaning depends on spline type)
.RE
.PP
\fBSee also\fP
.RS 4
\fBaddPoint()\fP, \fBgetFirstOrder()\fP, \fBgetSecondOrder()\fP 
.RE
.PP

